The issue here is that you're compiling with `/MD` (using the dynamic CRT) but then excluding the default MSVCRT with `/NODEFAULTLIB:MSVCRT`. This creates a manifest dependency conflict.

Here are several solutions:

## Solution 1: Use static CRT (Recommended for static linking)
```cmd
cl /MT /c test001.c /DXML_STATIC=1 /IC:\libxml2vc\include\libxml2
link test001.obj /LIBPATH:C:\libxml2vc\lib libxml2s.lib /LIBPATH:C:\buildzlib zlibstaticd.lib /LIBPATH:C:\GnuWin32\lib libiconv.lib bcrypt.lib
```

## Solution 2: Fix the manifest for dynamic CRT
If you want to keep `/MD`, you need to embed the manifest properly:

```cmd
cl /MD /c test001.c /DXML_STATIC=1 /IC:\libxml2vc\include\libxml2
link test001.obj /LIBPATH:C:\libxml2vc\lib libxml2s.lib /LIBPATH:C:\buildzlib zlibstaticd.lib /LIBPATH:C:\GnuWin32\lib libiconv.lib bcrypt.lib
mt.exe -manifest test001.exe.manifest -outputresource:test001.exe;1
```

## Solution 3: Remove the `/NODEFAULTLIB:MSVCRT` flag
Just remove the problematic flag:
```cmd
cl /MD /c test001.c /DXML_STATIC=1 /IC:\libxml2vc\include\libxml2
link test001.obj /LIBPATH:C:\libxml2vc\lib libxml2s.lib /LIBPATH:C:\buildzlib zlibstaticd.lib /LIBPATH:C:\GnuWin32\lib libiconv.lib bcrypt.lib
```

## Solution 4: Use the Windows SDK mt.exe tool
If Solution 2 doesn't work, find `mt.exe` (usually in Windows SDK) and use it explicitly:
```cmd
# After linking...
"c:\Program Files (x86)\Windows Kits\10\bin\10.0.17763.0\x86\mt.exe" -manifest test001.exe.manifest -outputresource:test001.exe;1
```

## Why this happens:
- `/MD` tells the compiler to use the dynamic CRT (MSVCRT)
- `/NODEFAULTLIB:MSVCRT` tells the linker to ignore the default CRT library
- This creates inconsistency between what the executable expects (manifest) and what it actually links

**I recommend Solution 1** (`/MT`) since you're already statically linking libxml2 and zlib, so consistent static linking makes sense.

